{{Infobox rockunit | name = Cheuquemó Formation | image = | caption = | type = | period = Miocene | age = [[Oligocene|Late Oligocene]]–[[Miocene|Early Miocene]] | prilithology = [[conglomerate (geology)|Conglomerate]], [[sandstone]], [[mudstone]], [[tuff]] | otherlithology = [[Coal]] | namedfor = | namedby = [[Floreal García]], 1968 | region = [[Los Lagos Region]] | country = {{CHL}} | coordinates = | unitof = | subunits = | underlies = [[Santo Domingo Formation]] | overlies = [[Bahía Mansa Metamorphic Complex]] | thickness = more than {{convert|1200|m|ft|abbr=on}} | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }} '''Cheuquemó Formation''' ({{lang-es|Formación Cheuquemó}}) is a [[geological formation]] of [[sedimentary rock]] in [[Zona Sur|south-central Chile]]. The sediments of the formation were deposited during the [[Oligocene|Late Oligocene]] and [[Miocene|Early Miocene]] epochs. The formations lower sections are made up of [[conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]], then successions of [[sandstone]], [[tuff]] and [[mudstone]] rich in organic material follows. The formation indicates that sedimentation occurred in a [[estuary|estuarine]] (paralic) and other non-marine (continental) environments. It contains fossils of the following genera: ''[[Mytilus (bivalve)|Mytilus]]'', ''[[Cardium]]'' and ''[[Turritella]]''. [[Stratigraphy|Stratigraphically]] it overlies the [[Bahía Mansa Metamorphic Complex]] and underlies the Miocene [[Santo Domingo Formation]].<ref name=Elguetaetal2000>{{cite book| author-last=Elgueta |author-first=Sara| author-last2=Le Roux |author-first2=Jacobus | author-last3=Duhart |author-first3=Paul|date=2000 | author-last4=McDonough|author-first4=Michael | author-last5=Urqueta|author-first5=Esteban |title=Estratigrafía y sedimentología de la cuencas terciarias de la Región de Los Lagos (39-41°30’S)|language=Spanish|publisher=[[National Geology and Mining Service|Servicio Nacional de Geología y Minería]]|pages= 15–16| place = Santiago, Chile| ISSN = 0020-3939}}</ref>
== Description == The formation is very similar to the [[Estratos de Pupunahue|Pupunahue Beds]] found further north, with the sole difference that the fossil assemblage in both seem to indicate different ages. While Cheuquemó is possibly about 14 million years old (Miocene), the Pupunahue Beds are 35–25 million years old.<ref>{{cite conference |url= |title=El yacimiento de carbón Catamutún (La Unión) |last1=Alfaro |first1=G.|last2=Gantz |first2=E.|last3=Magna |first3=O.|date=1990 |publisher=Departamento de Geociencias, Facultad de Ciencias, [[Universidad de Concepción]] |book-title=Actas |pages=11–28 |location=Santiago, Chile |conference=Segundo Simposio sobre el Terciario de Chile |id= |language=Spanish}}</ref>
